Question_Text: Where in your body do you feel ‘threat’ first during conflict (jaw, chest, gut)?
What behavior in other people makes you instantly contemptuous? (Name it precisely.)
When you feel challenged, do you become louder, colder, faster, or more sarcastic?
In disagreement, do you pursue (push) or withdraw (go silent)? Which is default?
What story do you tell yourself about weakness (unsafe, shameful, incompetent)?
What is your ‘control move’ under stress (micromanage, criticize, overwork, withdraw)?
When you are wrong mid-argument, do you double down, freeze, or admit immediately?
What do you call ‘high standards’ that is actually fear of being judged?
Who in your life can tell you the truth without you punishing them?
If you had to name your default ego defense (humor, intellect, anger, withdrawal), what is it?
Whose failure would secretly feel satisfying — and what does that reveal about you?
What trait you criticize in others do you fear is true about you?
What fear do you disguise as ‘logic’ when making leadership decisions?
What is your certainty addiction: where do you demand guarantees that life cannot provide?
What does it cost you to always be ‘the competent one’? (relationships, sleep, play)
If you weren’t allowed to achieve for 30 days, who would you be?
When someone is emotional, do you translate it into ‘data’ to avoid vulnerability?
What is your apology style: repair or reputation management?
Under stress, what leadership behavior shows up (interrupt, nitpick, withdraw, dominate)?
What do you do that looks like ‘responsibility’ but is actually control?
What part of you feels ‘exiled’ (playful, soft, needy, creative)?
What do you envy in others (freedom, ease, love, talent)?
What compliment makes you uncomfortable — and why?
When you feel shame, do you attack, explain, withdraw, or perform? Which is default?
What boundary do you enforce too late (or not at all) at work or at home?
What is the rule you learned about power (never show weakness / never ask / never lose)?
What is the ‘unlived life’ you still fantasize about, and what emotion sits under it?
What do you do to avoid being seen as ordinary?
What behavior do you justify as ‘efficiency’ that actually reduces trust?
Do you trust people until they give a reason not to, or mistrust until proven?
How often do you confuse being right with being safe?
What would you do if you didn’t have to prove anything for 24 hours?
When stressed, what do you ‘optimize’ to avoid feeling? (tasks, metrics, people)
What belief about vulnerability would you like to retire?
Who is the person you can be silent with without pressure? What makes it safe?
What are you afraid you will become if you relax?
What do you do that feels like ‘discipline’ but is actually self-punishment?
What mistake do you refuse to forgive yourself for — and what identity would collapse if you did forgive it?
Write your ‘repair script’ in one sentence: how do you reopen after conflict?
Name one boundary you will enforce this week (what, with whom, and the exact sentence).
What is one behavior you will stop doing when stressed (interrupting, nitpicking, withdrawing)?
Pick one belief to deprecate (old script). Write the replacement belief in 10 words.
Identify one situation where you will say ‘I don’t know’ this week without compensating.
Who will you ask for feedback (one person) and what question will you ask?
Choose one ‘exiled part’ to reintroduce (play/rest/creativity). What is the smallest act?
What regulation tool will you use before a hard conversation (breath, walk, water, pause)?
Define your ‘shutdown protocol’ after conflict (what you do in the next 30 minutes).
Name the single highest-leverage shadow pattern you found. Write it as: IF trigger → THEN defense.
Name 2 strengths that stay intact under stress (your actual toolkit).
Who is your ‘safe person’ for repair, and what makes them safe?
